1) Define the name of the folder you are in
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ pwd
/c/Users/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test

2) Create a folder named test1
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ mkdir test1

3) Go to the test1 folder
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ cd test1

4) Create file 1,2 and 3 inside the test1 directory
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test1 (main)
$ touch file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt

5) Check the contents of the test1 directory
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test1 (main)
$ ls
file1.txt  file2.txt  file3.txt

6) Create a test2 folder inside the home directory
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test1 (main)
$ cd ..

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ mkdir test2

7) Remove the test2 folder
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ rmdir test2

8) Delete File 2
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ cd test1

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test1 (main)
$ rm file2.txt

9) Create a test3 folder and add two files to it
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ mkdir test3

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ cd test3

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test3 (main)
$ touch file1.txt file2.txt

10) Remove the test3 folder
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test3 (main)
$ cd ..

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ rm -rf test3

11) Create a test4 folder
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ mkdir test4

12) Move files 1 and 3 to the test4 folder
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ mv test1/file1.txt test4

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ mv test1/file3.txt test4

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test (main)
$ cd test4

13) Add three lines with the word "line" to file 1
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ echo line > file1.txt

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ echo line >> file1.txt

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ echo line >> file1.txt

14) View file contents 1
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ cat file1.txt
line
line
line

15) Add 3 lines with line words to the file
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ echo line > file3.txt

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ echo line >> file3.txt

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ echo line >> file3.txt

16) Review the contents of two files (1 and 3) at once
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ cat file1.txt file3.txt
line
line
line
line
line
line

17) Use one of the editors to replace all lines
mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ nano file1.txt

mezhuev@MacBook-Pro-Mezhuev ~/Desktop/home_work/git_training/test/test4 (main)
$ cat file1.txt
create
create
create
